In this dialogue, the speaker is trying to explain that there are two different ways of looking at something (the concept of "kāraṇam" or cause), and that these two ways can lead to different conclusions about what is ultimately real. The speaker is using a metaphor of two people (A and B) who have different perspectives on the same issue, and are arguing with each other about what is true. The speaker is suggesting that both perspectives have some validity, but that they cannot be fully reconciled.

In this dialogue, two people are discussing the meaning of a proverb. One person (A) explains that the proverb means "the one who is not born will not die," while the other person (B) disagrees and says that it actually means "the one who does not exist will not be born."
